│ THOUGHT: Now I need to understand the issue. The problem is that when `%x = -inf`, `%cmp1 = fcmp ninf olt float %x, C` is poison because `-inf < C` with `ninf` flag (no infinities) makes the comparison      │
│ poison. However, `%cmp2 = fcmp ogt float %x, -C` is false because `-inf > -C` is false. So the select returns false. But the transformed code `fcmp ninf olt fabs(x), C` is poison because `fabs(-inf)` with   │
│ `ninf` flag is poison, making the comparison poison. The transformation incorrectly introduces poison.                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The issue is in the propagation of fast math flags. The transformation combines flags from both fcmp instructions: `Builder.setFastMathFlags(LHS->getFastMathFlags() | RHS->getFastMathFlags());`. In our      │
│ case, LHS has `ninf` flag, RHS doesn't. The union includes `ninf`, which gets propagated to the fabs call and the new fcmp. But the original select would not be poison when RHS is false, regardless of LHS   │
│ being poison, because select with false as the second operand returns the third operand (false) without evaluating the first operand.                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Actually, looking more carefully: `select i1 %cmp2, i1 %cmp1, i1 false` - when `%cmp2` is false, it returns false without evaluating `%cmp1`. So poison in `%cmp1` doesn't matter if `%cmp2` is false. But the │
│ transformation creates `fabs` with `ninf` flag which is always poison for -inf input, making the whole result poison.                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The fix should be to not propagate `ninf` (and possibly `nnan`) flags from the LHS to the fabs when the transformation could introduce poison that wasn't present in the original. Actually, we need to check  │
│ if the flags from both sides are safe to propagate. Let me examine the code more carefully.                                                                                                                    │
