│ THOUGHT: The issue is that the transformation is only valid if the fast math flags from both operands are compatible and don't introduce new poison. Specifically, when we have `A && B` where A is `fcmp ogt  │
│ x, -C` (no ninf) and B is `fcmp ninf olt x, C`, the result is only poison when both A and B are evaluated and B is poison. But if A is false, B is not evaluated. The transformation evaluates fabs(x)         │
│ unconditionally with ninf flag, which is poison for -inf even when the original wouldn't be.                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ We need to check if we can safely propagate the flags. The fabs intrinsic with ninf flag will return poison for infinities. But in the original code, fabs isn't explicitly called. The comparison `fcmp ninf  │
│ olt x, C` is poison for -inf, but that poison only matters if the comparison is actually evaluated (when x > -C is true).                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Actually, let me think about this more carefully. In the original:                                                                                                                                             │
│ - `%cmp1 = fcmp ninf olt float %x, C` - poison if x is -inf (due to ninf)                                                                                                                                      │
│ - `%cmp2 = fcmp ogt float %x, -C` - false if x is -inf                                                                                                                                                         │
│ - `%cond = select i1 %cmp2, i1 %cmp1, i1 false` - returns false because %cmp2 is false                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The select doesn't evaluate %cmp1 when %cmp2 is false, so the poison in %cmp1 doesn't affect the result.                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ In the transformed version:                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ - `%1 = call ninf float @llvm.fabs.f32(float %x)` - poison if x is -inf (due to ninf)                                                                                                                          │
│ - `%cond = fcmp ninf olt float %1, C` - poison because %1 is poison                                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The transformation introduces poison where there was none. The fix is to not propagate ninf (and nnan) flags from comparisons that might not be evaluated in the original expression. We should only propagate │
│ flags that are present on both comparisons, or we need to be more careful about when flags can be propagated.                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Actually, looking at the code again: `Builder.setFastMathFlags(LHS->getFastMathFlags() | RHS->getFastMathFlags());` takes the union of flags. This is wrong for ninf and nnan because if only one side has     │
│ these flags, the other side might allow infinities/NaNs, and the original expression wouldn't be poison for those inputs when that side determines the result.                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ We should intersect the flags instead of unioning them for ninf and nnan. Or we should check if the transformation preserves poison behavior. Let me look for how other similar transformations handle this.   │
